nomenological concept of life in its affective and even vital dimensions, the emerging dialogue with the analytic philosophy of mind and language, and reassessments of the so-called theological turn.The diversity of approaches collected here has its origin in a deeper debate about the conceptual and historical foundations of phenomenology itself. In this way the book offers the most accessible and wide-ranging introduction to French phenomenology to have appeared in the English-speaking world to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPhenomenologistszFrancevInterviews. 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosopherszFrancevInterviews. 4aContinental Philosophy. 4aContinental and Analytic Philosophy. 4aFrench Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy and Theology. 4aTheological Turn. 4aphenomenology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aHackett, W. Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKearney, Richard08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823264742zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823264742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823264742.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK